What is the story of Zaharia, 82, a tale that cannot find justice in mere fleeting images? A generation born before and around World War Two, they have endured unyielding toughness throughout their lives, carrying it with them until the very end. Wars, famines, communismâ€”these trials have left just a handful of them behind. But as a nation, have we failed to protect them and provide the closure they deserve? In the villages where the young have departed to seek work in bustling cities or foreign lands, a poignant silence now lingers. Once vibrant communities, these villages embody a fading way of life. The simplicity of days spent tending to fields, the joyous gatherings celebrating harvests, and the warm hearths that nurtured tight-knit families have all waned with time. Now, the elders remain, reminiscing about a past that seems distant and unreal to the younger generations who have chosen different paths. The old ways, deeply rooted in tradition and close-knit bonds, now struggle to survive in the face of modernity's relentless advance. The resilience of these villagers stands as a testament to their enduring spirit, forged through enduring the darkest days of history. Yet, as they bear witness to the departure of their youth, a question lingers: Will the stories of their struggles and the beauty of their traditions find a place in the hearts of those who have moved on? Don't forget that Florida has many natural springs to explore! These two springs are located about 1hr away from Panama City Beach or Destin.  Ponce De Leon Springs- it's $4 per vehicle to get into the park and It's open from 8am until sunset all year. The spring water is 68 degrees Fahrenheit all year round so it is chilly! I saw people bring tubes with umbrellas to float around here and thought that was such a good idea! There are nature trails you can walk around as well.  Morrison Springs County Park- this spot is near Ponce De Leon and has more of a natural feel to it. It's a popular spot for diving and even has a small cave divers can go into! This is a great spot to kayak too. It includes a diving dock, boat ramp, and boardwalks. It's free to visit!  This was my favorite thing we did on our last Florida trip! However, I've noticed a lack of detailed information about running routes, especially in less-traveled locations. That's why I'm creating a series of videos reviewing hundreds of different runs from various places around the globe. In each video, I'll share insights about the location and the route itself. This Some kind of tourists in  our existence  The Black Desert is an area of volcano-shaped and widely separated mounds in western Egypt, stretching for around 30 kilometres (19 miles) between the White Desert in the south and the Bahariya Oasis in the north. Basalt sills cover the majority of its mounds, giving them their distinctive black appearance. The Black Desert's mounds, which may reach heights of 100 metres (328 feet), vary in size, composition, height, and shape, with some being black due to iron quartzite and others being more reddish due to iron sandstone. Volcanic hills on the fringes of the Black Desert show that black volcanic dolerite erupted 180 million years ago, indicating the Jurassic era. 1 Its soooo beautiful. It is volcano's lava. When you approach the mountain the lava are balck rocks. When you start walking up the mountain and you approach the summit, you realize that the volcano's lava made the rocks all pressed one against each other. Something phenominal. You just have to wear good climing boots or shoes. Some rocks are slippery. Must be careful. It is the highest summit in the black desert. I have never immagined that a desert can be or have a magical view  2 The Black Desert is located North from the White Desert, closer to Bahariya than Farafra. The name comes from the black volcanic hills and eroded material covering the sand with black stones and powder. The darkness contrasts with what you will experience few dozens of kilometers later, the White Desert, adding to the variety of Egyptian deserts. Winter and early spring nights are pretty chilly, so remember to take a good sleeping bag if you plan camping. Thinking about backpacking +10,000 km from Nairobi to South Africa? It's definitely cheaper than flying and there's a lot of bus options cutting through multiple countries from Kenya all the way to South Africa and back. At the moment there's no bus company doing a direct journey but it's easy enough to go capital city to capital city. In fact, the further south you go the more busing options there are. Here are some basics for any long distance backpacking trip: 1. Be patient- some border crossings will be super fast while others will take a lot of time, some people will not respond to your sense of urgency, some things won't work the way you expect them to.  2. Be flexible- have multiple plans so that you don't get stuck. Cars break down, government officials can be tricky, ailments will throw you off your game... 3. Be ready to jump at opportunities- your legs will swell up or cramp up, your back will be uncomfortable, your butt will ache so take all the breaks you get... including bathroom breaks! 4. Pack light- Take only what you need because hauling bags upon bags everywhere is not the life. 5. Tissue, water or wipes- yes to everything. You'll want to keep fresh while on the road so they come in super handy. 6. Plan ahead- Understand what your expenditure per country will be so that you change cash at the most opportune places. Get the country's sim card for easier comms and good internet. Both can be found at border crossings. Exercise good judgement when dealing with money at all times. 7. Luxury hotel v. Bed and breakfasts- If you need to catch an early morning bus it's easier to find somewhere to stay that's close (walking distance or short taxi ride). Obviously work within your budgets but check online deals as well as ask around for locals to give you recommendations.  8. Interact with locals - They know their environment better than you and the internet. Be open to new connections, spread some good cheer and make the best of all situations. Every trip will have it's specific set of requirements so do some research but all in all, go out there and explore!! #backpackingkenya #backpackingadventures #backpackinglife #travelsouthafrica #travelkenya

There are 3 ways to go from Bangkok to Chiang Mai: by air, by bus and by train. The best way to get from Bangkok to Chiang Mai is to fly which takes 3h 5m and costs approximately à¸¿1100 - à¸¿3200. Alternatively, you can take a bus via Sombat Tour, which costs around à¸¿500 - à¸¿1100 and takes 9h 12m. And last, but not least you could also take a night train, which costs à¸¿210 - à¸¿1600 and takes 10h 5m. I took the night train from Bangkok to Chiang Mai, which was fun and clean! The way back, from Chiang Mai to Bangkok, I took a bus, which was a total "nightmare". The bus was very old and full of cockroaches everywhere. I did not sleep at all that night. So I would recommend you to take a night train or a flight, instead of a bus. Amidst the silence, a giant tree spreads its branches wide, offering a sheltering canopy over the ulita. Its gnarled bark and outstretched limbs evoke a sense of timelessness, a silent witness to the ebb and flow of generations. Beneath its shade, an open fire crackles, casting dancing shadows that intertwine with memories etched into the villageâ€™s very soul. A pot hangs above the flames, its contents simmering with the essence of traditional flavors, a reminder of the nourishing traditions that sustain the spirit. As the dogs play and the sun dips lower, casting a warm, amber glow on the landscape, Maria finds her place on a weathered bench. The village may be deserted, but it teems with lifeâ€™s echo, resonating in the breeze that rustles through forgotten corners. Mariaâ€™s gaze is one of patient longing, a testament to the enduring spirit of those who remain, tethered to their roots and the stories that once reverberated through these deserted streets. In this quietude, one is compelled to ponder: what led to this emptiness, this haunting beauty of abandonment? Have you ventured to Rasnov, a town steeped in the legends of medieval Transylvania? Tucked away within the Carpathian Mountains, Rasnov is a place where history echoes through the narrow streets and ancient fortifications. At the heart of Rasnov stands the impressive Rasnov Citadel, a fortress that has watched over the town for centuries. This towering stone bastion, perched atop a hill, offers breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape. The fortress isn't just a relic of the past; it's a living testament to the resilience of the people who built it to defend against invaders. Rasnov's charm extends beyond its citadel. The town's Old Town, with its quaint houses and cobblestone streets, transports you to a time when horse-drawn carriages clattered through the lanes. Have you ever explored the hidden corners of Rasnov, discovering the stories etched into its walls and streets?  The town's rich history and stunning natural surroundings make it a captivating destination, inviting you to uncover its secrets and embrace its timeless allure. If you haven't yet had the pleasure of visiting Rasnov, isn't it time you embarked on this journey through the ages? About Serval Wildlife and the animals taken from their website: "Our sanctuary is over 1000 acres, prepared in phases and in accordance with the needs of our animals 50 acres at a time. Animals are ethically obtained from zoos & injured animals from the wild with the aim of instilling natural behaviors and eventually rehabilitating them into the wild with the assistance of TAWA and TAWIRI. The animals that reside within our wildlife sanctuary are owned by the Tanzanian Government and often brought to us by TAWA as orphans or injured wildlife. We treat and train our animals to prepare them for release into their natural habitat within TANAPA protected parks. Our wildlife sanctuary also doubles as an endangered species reintroduction platform to translocate animals to parts of its natural range where populations have significantly declined or been lost. Aiming to establish a viable population within translocated areas. Our most recent animals for release are our lions. Brought to us from other zoos due to being rejected by their mother at a very young age. Upon arrival these animals were in poor condition, we have trained them and nursed them back to health. 5 fascinating things about driving in italy ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡¹ğŸ“ 01:- ZTL Zones (Limited Traffic Zones): Many Italian cities, especially historic centers like Rome and Florence, have Zona a Traffico Limitato (ZTL), restricted areas where only residents, taxis, and delivery vehicles can enter during certain hours. Tourists often receive fines for unknowingly driving into these zones! 02:- Autostrada Toll Roads: Italy's autostrada highways are well-maintained but are often toll roads. Drivers take a ticket upon entering and pay when exiting, based on the distance traveled. 03:- Speed Cameras and Fines: Italy is strict on speeding, and speed cameras are common on highways and city roads. Speeding fines can be mailed to you even if you're a foreign driver, thanks to plate tracking. 04:- Unique Parking Rules: Parking spaces are color-coded in Italy: white lines are for free parking, blue lines indicate paid parking, and yellow lines are reserved for residents, disabled drivers, or specific vehicles. 05:- Roundabouts with a Twist: In Italy, drivers in roundabouts generally give priority to vehicles entering the roundabout, unless specified otherwise by signageâ€”opposite of what is common in many other countries! #DrivingInItaly  #ItalianRoadTrip  #carculture   #exploreitaly  #roadtripvibes  #travelgoals  #italyadventures  #funfacts  #wanderlust  #traveltips

During a time when gathering in public was severely restricted and cultural expressions like tango and carnival were banned, these brave mothers found a way to protest peacefully. Their struggle is a poignant reminder of the power of peaceful protest and the enduring strength of maternal love. Despite facing the same grim fate as their children, the Mothers of Plaza de Mayo remain a symbol of resistance and hope, continuing their demonstrations to this day. When visiting Detroit, you have to get Detroit-style pizza. A great place to get some is at Buddy's Pizza. My nieces, nephew, and I went to the original location on Conant Street which has been around since 1946. Detroit-style pizza is a rectangular deep dish pizza which has a crispy crust, rich cheese, flavorful toppings, and lots of sauce. Every bite is packed full of flavor. What is great is that everyone can join in the fun as they even have vegan and gluten-free options! Make sure to get the full experience of Buddy's Pizza by bringing your friends and family to join in the fun! I want to give a very special thanks to my nieces and my nephew for coming out to join in the adventure! They are some of my biggest supporters, and I truly appreciate and care for every one of them! #buddyspizza #detroitpizza #detroitstylepizza #detroitfood #detroitrestaurants #puremichigan #detroittravel #visitdetroit #exploredetroit #michiganfood #michiganrestaurants #visitmichigan #exploremichigan #michigantravel #michigantraveler #michiganfoodie #foodietravel #detroitfoodie

Full day Tour  From $55pp Depart from Cape Town in a luxury air-conditioned coach and head directly to the Franschhoek valley to join the Franschhoek hop-on hop-off wine tram and bus. The Franschhoek Wine Tram offers two hop-on hop-off lines (clockwise & anti-clockwise), each visiting various wine estates in the Franschhoek Valley. Enjoy transportation to each wine estate every hour by a combination of tram and tram-buses around the loop. Each stop is at a different wine estate, allowing you to hop on and hop off at any of the estates. The tram or tram passes each stop once an hour, so you can explore at your convenience to move from one estate to the next. Head back to the Franschhoek Wine Tram station for your transfer back to Cape Town You can select from five different routes, each of which takes you to various wine estates that highlight different aspects of the Franschhoek Valley. With the Hop-on Hop-off experience, you have the freedom to design and organize your own day. You can decide how much time you want to spend at each location (within the line's schedule, naturally), where you want to dine, where you want to enjoy some wine, and which activities you'd like to participate in. Your adventure commences at either the Franschhoek Terminal or the Groot Drakenstein Terminal, depending on the route you've chosen. While you wait for your journey to commence, you can grab a coffee, savor a beignet, and explore our selection of merchandise. The concept of "proof that anything can be a Netflix poster" demonstrates the cinematic potential in everyday scenes, transforming mundane moments into striking visual narratives, akin to those that grace the promotional materials of movies and TV shows. This phenomenon explores how ordinary settings can be depicted with an artistic flair that captures the imagination, similar to the vivid, engaging posters we see on Netflix. Imagine a scene set in Cala Figuera, a picturesque fishing village renowned for its idyllic coastal beauty. This particular narrative unfolds at a seafood restaurant, perched by the edge of the sea, offering diners not just exquisite dishes but also a panoramic view of the Mediterranean. The restaurant bustles with activity, its atmosphere a blend of local charm and the refreshing sea breeze. As the sun sets, it bathes the restaurant and its patrons in a golden light, creating a backdrop ripe for a Netflix poster. Through the lens of a skilled photographer or filmmaker, this scene could be captured in a way that emphasizes its dramatic and aesthetic qualities. The setting sun, the gently rocking boats in the harbor, and the lively atmosphere inside the restaurant come together to create a snapshot of life that feels both intimate and expansive. The use of lighting, the composition of the frame, and the expressions of the people combine to tell a story that goes beyond mere dining; it speaks to the joy of shared experiences in beautiful places. This image could easily be envisioned as a poster for a travel or culinary documentary, perhaps titled "Seaside Feasts: Cala Figuera". The poster could feature the vibrant colors of the sky and sea, the silhouette of a boat gently swaying in the harbor, and the lively scene of diners enjoying their meals, all framed to invite the viewer into this captivating world. Such a poster would not only draw viewers with its visual appeal but also with the promise of exploring the cultural and culinary richness of Cala Figuera. It serves as a testament to the power of visual storytelling and the ability of photographers and filmmakers to find profound beauty and narrative potential in everyday locations. Rahasia Kelezatan Kuliner di Jantung Hutan Tanjung Puting Menjelajahi Taman Nasional Tanjung Puting bukan hanya tentang petualangan di alam liar, tapi juga tentang menikmati kelezatan kuliner yang tak terduga. Di atas kelotok, para juru masak handal Lookorangutan siap memanjakan lidah Anda dengan hidangan istimewa. Bukan sekadar juru masak biasa, mereka tergabung dalam Perkumpulan Asosiasi Chef Tanjung Puting, yang rutin berlatih untuk menyajikan: Menu bergizi dan seimbang: Pagi, siang, sore, dan snack, semua tersusun dengan pertimbangan nutrisi dan selera. Variasi menu: Menu Indonesia, Asia, dan Barat tersedia, dengan pilihan vegetarian, rendah garam, dan tanpa MSG. Pesan khusus: Lobster, udang galah, dan hidangan mewah lainnya dapat disiapkan sesuai permintaan. Pengalaman istimewa: Lebih dari 6 orang tamu akan ditemani 2 juru masak untuk memastikan kelezatan setiap hidangan. Hawa hutan dan panorama alam yang memesona akan menambah kenikmatan setiap suapan.
